<br>
Anyways, Here's my take.  I think world, no one is totally honest.  A husband will tell his wife there were no women on a guys' night out, even though they were flirting with 18 year old girls the whole time.  A child will tell him mom that he didn't break the vase, that the cat did it.  In even small situations, with small consequences, no one is totally honest.  Take a much larger situation like.... oh I don't know, nuclear war.  We tell Russia, China, India, crazy ass Middle Eastern countries and most importantly, Canada, that we'll get rid of all ours, if they do.<br>
<br>
Great plan, so we sign a treaty called &quot;Down with Nukes, Let's get drunk and Puke&quot;.  Hypothetically, let's say we just screwed one of those countries on an international trade deal.  Something sort of minor, like we forgot to send Canada their monthly supply of......marijuana.  Canada says, &quot;Yes, all of our nukes are gone, as well as all of your, China, Russia and Kerblakistan's&quot;.  The world is in rejoice.<br>
<br>
What you don't know is those sneaky Bloodthirsty neighbors to the north didn't really get rid of &quot;all&quot; their nukes.  They forgot about those 5 silos or so in the complete bareassed wilderness.  Who has the upperhand now?<br>
<br>
My point is this.  Nuclear warfare has been a topic of discussion, non-stop since we started it all in 1945.  It will never stop being a topic until we blow each other up in a massive collision.  No one is trustworthy in politics.  If you Russia says they have 200,000 nukes, they have 500,000 and some stashed away at their mom's house from back in highschool.  If China says they disarmed 100,000, they just made 200,000 in a factory.  If we say we're going to disarm all of our nukes, we've already launched 10 at key positions in Mongolia, damn Mongols.<br>
<br>
To trust a man that is a politician, is to trust a snake, when it says it won't bite.<br>
<br>
